<p>Although we don't say so, we can prove that <math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3=
.org/1998/Math/MathML" display=3D"inline" class=3D"maruku-mathml"><semantic=
s><mrow><mo>=E2=8A=A4</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex"=
>\top</annotation></semantics></math>, <math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/199=
8/Math/MathML" display=3D"inline" class=3D"maruku-mathml"><semantics><mrow>=
<mo>=E2=8A=A5</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">\bot</a=
nnotation></semantics></math>, <math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/M=
athML" display=3D"inline" class=3D"maruku-mathml"><semantics><mrow><mi>a</m=
i><mo>=E2=88=A7</mo><mi>b</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-=
tex">a \wedge b</annotation></semantics></math>, <math xmlns=3D"http://www.=
w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display=3D"inline" class=3D"maruku-mathml"><semant=
ics><mrow><mi>a</mi><mo>=E2=88=A8</mo><mi>b</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=
=3D"application/x-tex">a \vee b</annotation></semantics></math>, and <math =
xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display=3D"inline" class=3D"ma=
ruku-mathml"><semantics><mrow><mo>=C2=AC</mo><mi>a</mi></mrow><annotation e=
ncoding=3D"application/x-tex">\neg{a}</annotation></semantics></math> are u=
nique; this makes it more clear what the last two axioms actually mean.</p>

<p>Notice that a poset carries at most one Boolean algebra structure, makin=
g it <a class=3D"existingWikiWord" href=3D"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/st=
uff%2C+structure%2C+property">property-like structure</a>. (The same is tru=
e of <a class=3D"existingWikiWord" href=3D"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/He=
yting+algebra">Heyting algebra</a> structure.)</p>

<p>Alternatively, a <strong>Boolean algebra</strong> is a <a class=3D"exist=
ingWikiWord" href=3D"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/set">set</a> equipped wi=
th elements <math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display=3D"i=
nline" class=3D"maruku-mathml"><semantics><mrow><mo>=E2=8A=A4</mo></mrow><a=
nnotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">\top</annotation></semantics></mat=
h> and <math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display=3D"inline=
" class=3D"maruku-mathml"><semantics><mrow><mo>=E2=8A=A5</mo></mrow><annota=
tion encoding=3D"application/x-tex">\bot</annotation></semantics></math>, b=
inary operations <math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display=
=3D"inline" class=3D"maruku-mathml"><semantics><mrow><mo>=E2=88=A7</mo></mr=
ow><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">\wedge</annotation></semantic=
s></math> and <math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display=3D=
"inline" class=3D"maruku-mathml"><semantics><mrow><mo>=E2=88=A8</mo></mrow>=
<annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">\vee</annotation></semantics></m=
ath>, and a unary operation <math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/Math=
ML" display=3D"inline" class=3D"maruku-mathml"><semantics><mrow><mo>=C2=AC<=
/mo></mrow><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">\neg</annotation></se=
mantics></math>, satisfying these identities:</p>

<ol>
<li><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display=3D"inline" c=
lass=3D"maruku-mathml"><semantics><mrow><mi>a</mi><mo>=E2=88=A7</mo><mo>=E2=
